Defendant Hunter J Marks in court with attorney Brian Christopher Hagner.  William T. Berens appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  
cab
Statements made as to sentencing.  
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 24 MONTHS, with credit for 2 DAYS time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 17 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 7 MONTHS.  The defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Earned Release Program.
The Court STAYED this sentence and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 2 YEARS with the following conditions:
*   As a condition of probation, the Court ordered the defendant to serve 60 days in the House of Correction, with no release privileges.  This time is stayed pending a review on 11/20/2015 at 01:30 pm
*   Successfully complete "Batterers intervention" counseling.
*   Obtain an AODA assessment and follow-up treatment;
*   Maintain absolute sobriety with random urine screens - no illegal drugs; 
*   No contact with victim.  No other modification without the approval of the court.  
*   Defendant may have contact with the victim through a third party to arrange time with children.
*   Defendant to have a mental health evaluation and cooperate with any treatment.
*   Defendant to participate in a parenting class.
*   Obtain/maintain employment; 
*   Pay supervision fees;
*   Provide a DNA sample - pay surcharge;
*   Pay all remaining costs, surcharges and assessments during the period of probation or a civil judgment will be issued.
*   Defendant to pay restitution in the amount of $628.00 through agent.
The Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon he/she may not vote until his/her civil rights are restored and he/she may never possess a firearm.
